1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,080
Hi everyone, my name is Ian Barash and this is my practicum project, the Multi-Signature

2
00:00:06,080 --> 00:00:09,100
Authentication Web Proxy.

3
00:00:09,100 --> 00:00:14,960
Basic ideas, it's like MFA, but the factors are people.

4
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:20,900
I got the idea from Crypto Wallets, they've already solved this.

5
00:00:20,900 --> 00:00:28,860
To be able to move funds from a critical account, you usually need to have multiple people sign

6
00:00:28,860 --> 00:00:37,240
the request with their keys before the transaction is sent to the end user.

7
00:00:37,240 --> 00:00:43,240
This means that no one person can forward millions of dollars on their own.

8
00:00:43,240 --> 00:00:45,400
The group has to agree first.

9
00:00:45,400 --> 00:00:49,840
And the security comes from the cooperation rather than trusting one individual with the

10
00:00:49,840 --> 00:00:51,360
keys.

11
00:00:51,360 --> 00:00:55,320
However, web logins still trust one person.

12
00:00:55,320 --> 00:01:01,120
Things like a duo or if you self-host Othalia, they prove who you are, but none of them require

13
00:01:01,120 --> 00:01:08,560
several distinct people to cooperate before granting access to a service.

14
00:01:08,560 --> 00:01:13,640
The idea is a web proxy that grants access only when a quorum of approvers each provide

15
00:01:13,640 --> 00:01:15,280
their secret key.

16
00:01:15,280 --> 00:01:23,080
It'll sit in front of any web service and when a request is sent, it is caught, held,

17
00:01:23,080 --> 00:01:30,640
and only released after enough people sign off on that request.

18
00:01:30,640 --> 00:01:37,920
And ideally, no changes to the back-end application will be required.

19
00:01:37,920 --> 00:01:38,920
Why does it matter?

20
00:01:38,920 --> 00:01:42,880
Well, right now, one developer holds the keys to the kingdom.

21
00:01:42,880 --> 00:01:48,960
Supply chain attacks on MPM and PiPI keep succeeding because compromising a single account

22
00:01:48,960 --> 00:01:53,520
allows the attacker to ship malicious code to everyone downstream.

23
00:01:53,520 --> 00:02:01,160
Without this, compromising one account turns into compromising the entire internet.

24
00:02:01,160 --> 00:02:02,160
How's it going to work?

25
00:02:02,160 --> 00:02:08,280
Well, like I mentioned, it'll intercept requests to an endpoint.

26
00:02:08,280 --> 00:02:13,680
It'll then notify approvers on a defined access list.

27
00:02:13,680 --> 00:02:20,960
It'll wait until a quorum is achieved, until enough people agree to that request, and it'll

28
00:02:20,960 --> 00:02:26,360
be forwarded along to the endpoint.

29
00:02:26,360 --> 00:02:28,960
Let's look at this use case concretely.

30
00:02:28,960 --> 00:02:32,280
So publishing a package to PiPI.

31
00:02:32,280 --> 00:02:36,760
For those of you who don't know, publishing a package is just HTTP.

32
00:02:36,760 --> 00:02:44,280
So when a maintainer runs publish, instead of sending it to the public repository, they'll

33
00:02:44,280 --> 00:02:47,640
be sending it to this web proxy.

34
00:02:47,640 --> 00:02:52,840
It'll intercept and save the release instead of pushing it directly to the public.

35
00:02:52,840 --> 00:02:58,560
The other maintainers are going to be notified that a package is awaiting release.

36
00:02:58,560 --> 00:03:04,640
Approvals will be gathered until the quorum is reached, and then and only then will that

37
00:03:04,640 --> 00:03:11,280
package be published to the public repository, stopping any one individual from publishing

38
00:03:11,280 --> 00:03:14,040
it themselves.

39
00:03:14,040 --> 00:03:15,960
Now it's still in the research phase.

40
00:03:15,960 --> 00:03:24,160
This week I spent a lot of time refining and defining the problem, trying to find motivation

41
00:03:24,160 --> 00:03:33,440
in real world use cases that are realistic and will help the security community.

42
00:03:33,440 --> 00:03:41,480
I have found that package repository use case and have began researching some multi-signature

43
00:03:41,480 --> 00:03:47,240
crypto primitives that will underlie the authentication scheme.

44
00:03:47,240 --> 00:03:53,040
Next week I hope to choose an authentication scheme, write some of the high level architecture

45
00:03:53,040 --> 00:04:02,280
and data flow specifications, and then specify some of the systems and how they'll work.

46
00:04:02,280 --> 00:04:07,360
So three things I'd like your input on.

47
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:11,280
I'm still trying to figure out how to prevent bypassing the proxy.

48
00:04:11,280 --> 00:04:17,840
I've thought if it's a web account that you're protecting, the web proxy will probably need

49
00:04:17,840 --> 00:04:25,800
your credentials rather than allowing any user to have them.

50
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:30,160
But for other things, it's a little trickier.

51
00:04:30,160 --> 00:04:33,960
Also the signature scheme that will underlie this.

52
00:04:33,960 --> 00:04:42,000
Has anybody used any cryptographic multi-signature primitives or know of any that may be helpful

53
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:44,160
here?

54
00:04:44,160 --> 00:04:48,800
I've done some research, but it's by no means conclusive.

55
00:04:48,800 --> 00:04:50,360
And where else does this apply?

56
00:04:50,360 --> 00:04:56,260
I've thought of that package publishing, but where else could requiring multiple people

57
00:04:56,260 --> 00:05:00,700
to approve of a web request be useful in the real world?

58
00:05:00,700 --> 00:05:02,580
That's all the time I have.

59
00:05:02,580 --> 00:05:04,940
So thank you and I'll see you in a few weeks.

